In Article <strnlghtCFn0qM.8Fv@netcom.com>
strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:

>If PKP agrees that this is a licensed product, it comes as very good news 
>indeed for DOS users who wish a "U.S. non-infringing" version of PGP, (and
>when the Mac version comes out, good news to Mac users) who wish to
>communicate with others who use PGP, and/or believe that IDEA is more secure
>than the triple DES available in competing implementations.

I'm sure you'll want to check for yourself, but I spoke with the PKP folks way
back at Interop and they confirmed the ViaCrypt license. They also said that
ViaCrypt made its initial announcement before the license was granted by almost
a month. If they had failed to get an agreement, it would have been kind of
embarrassing!

